{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# SciPy (the Scientific Python Library)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Summary of what we have learned so far:\n",
    "\n",
    "1) `numpy` supplies many common statistics and math functions for operating on arrays.\n",
    "2) `netCDF4` and `pandas` allow you to read in multidimensional and labeled data.\n",
    "3) `matplotlib` generates many standard plot types (line plots, scatter, images, contours, histograms)\n",
    "\n",
    " What about more complex operations such as filtering? How do people generate such _fancy_ statistics plots? "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "[SciPy](https://scipy.org/) is an all-purpose scientific Python library that operates on NumPy arrays where you will find the following (and much more!):\n",
    "\n",
    "1) [scipy.signal](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/signal.html): convolution, filtering, peak finding, spectral analysis\n",
    "\n",
    "2) [scipy.fft](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/fft.html): fft, ifft, fftshift, sin and cos transforms\n",
    "\n",
    "3) [scipy.optimize](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/optimize.html): curve fitting, root finding, nonlinear least squares, minimization\n",
    "\n",
    "4) [scipy.linalg](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/linalg.html): matrix functions, decompositions, inv, eig\n",
    "\n",
    "5) [scipy.interpolate](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/interpolate.html): univariate and multivariate interpolation, cubic splines, smoothing and approximation\n",
    "\n",
    "6) [scipy.integrate](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/integrate.html): single/double/triple definite integrals, integrating over fixed samples, numerical methods (Runge-Kutta, Initial Value problems)\n",
    "\n",
    "7) [scipy.stats](https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/stats.html): continuous distributions, discrete distributions, multivariate distributions, summary stats, frequency stats, correlation and association, resampling and Monte Carlo methods\n",
    "\n",
    "You can consider SciPy tools to be roughly equivalent to tools you would find in Matlab or R. SciPy is also heavily tested, has millions of users, and regular maintainers."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Data Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's load the pier temperature data from our last workshop session. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np # numpy is usually imported as np (but doesn't have to be)\n",
    "from netCDF4 import Dataset, num2date\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "\n",
    "# import netcdf dataset\n",
    "nc = Dataset('scripps_pier-2023.nc', mode='r')\n",
    "\n",
    "# select salinity and time variables\n",
    "temp = nc.variables['temperature'][:]\n",
    "time = num2date(nc.variables['time'][:], nc.variables['time'].units, only_use_cftime_datetimes=False)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Create Figure \n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the first 10 variables\n",
    "axes.plot(time, temp)\n",
    "axes.set_xlabel('Time')\n",
    "axes.set_ylabel('Temperature (deg C)')\n",
    "axes.grid(True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display figure\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Detrend and Filter with scipy.signal"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First, let's turn our timeseries of temperature, into a timeseries of temperature anomaly."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "0.00014015801\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from scipy import signal \n",
    "\n",
    "# detrend our data \n",
    "temp_anomaly = signal.detrend(temp)\n",
    "print(np.mean(temp_anomaly))  # should be close to zero"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))\n",
    "# Plot the first 10 variables\n",
    "axes.plot(time, temp_anomaly)\n",
    "axes.axhline(np.mean(temp_anomaly),linestyle='--', color='red', label='Mean')\n",
    "axes.set_xlabel('Time')\n",
    "axes.set_ylabel('Temperature (deg C)')\n",
    "axes.grid(True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display figure\n",
    "plt.show()\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "That data is pretty noisy! We can filter it to remove signals that are shorter period than 1 day. Looking at the figure below, our data appears to be taken every 5 minutes."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Create Figure \n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the first 10 variables\n",
    "axes.plot(time[:10], temp_anomaly[:10])\n",
    "axes.set_xlabel('Time')\n",
    "axes.set_ylabel('Temperature (deg C)')\n",
    "axes.grid(True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display figure\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "dt_minutes = 5 # timestep in minutes\n",
    "fs = 1440 / dt_minutes  # sampling frequency, minutes/day / minutes/sample = samples/day\n",
    "nyquist = fs / 2 \n",
    "\n",
    "# Cutoff\n",
    "cutoff_cpd = 1.0  # cycles per day\n",
    "Wn = cutoff_cpd / nyquist\n",
    "\n",
    "# Design filter\n",
    "order = 4\n",
    "sos = signal.butter(order, Wn, btype='low', output='sos')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Apply filtering\n",
    "filtered = signal.sosfiltfilt(sos, temp_anomaly)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Create Figure \n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,5))\n",
    "\n",
    "axes.plot(time, filtered)\n",
    "axes.axhline(np.mean(filtered),linestyle='--', color='red', label='Mean')\n",
    "axes.set_xlabel('Time')\n",
    "axes.set_ylabel('Temperature (deg C)')\n",
    "axes.grid(True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Display figure\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Fitting a Distribution with scipy.stats"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Perhaps we want a way to summarize our temperature anomaly data. One way to do this is to fit a distribution to it. Naively we can start with a normal distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "4.5219205500316825e-05 1.9543337126378342\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 800x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from scipy import stats\n",
    "\n",
    "mu, sigma = stats.norm.fit(filtered, method=\"MLE\")  # do a maximum-likelihood fit of a normal distribution\n",
    "print(mu, sigma) # print out the mean and standard deviation\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot figure\n",
    "bins = np.arange(mu - 4 * sigma, mu + 4 * sigma, 0.5) # create bins for histogram using the mean and + or - 4 standard deviations\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,5))\n",
    "axes.hist(filtered, density=True, histtype='stepfilled',\n",
    "         alpha=0.2, label='Samples',bins=bins)\n",
    "axes.plot(bins, stats.norm.pdf(bins, loc=mu, scale=sigma),\n",
    "         'k-', lw=2, label='Fit')\n",
    "axes.set_xlabel('Temperature (deg C)')\n",
    "axes.set_ylabel('Probability Density')\n",
    "axes.legend(loc='best', frameon=False)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Kurtosis: -0.17225053286842096, Skew: 0.5672473389299741\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# how good is a normal distribution? lets use kurtosis and skew \n",
    "kurt = stats.kurtosis(filtered)\n",
    "skw = stats.skew(filtered)\n",
    "print(f'Kurtosis: {kurt}, Skew: {skw}')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This distribution appears to be skewed toward positive temperature anomalies. Since the distribution looks roughly normal, but with a slight skew, we can try a skew-normal distribution."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Shape (a)  = 3.805\n",
      "Location   = -2.427\n",
      "Scale      = 3.116\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 800x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Fit skew-normal: returns shape, loc, scale\n",
    "a_hat, loc_hat, scale_hat = stats.skewnorm.fit(filtered)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Shape (a)  = {a_hat:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Location   = {loc_hat:.3f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Scale      = {scale_hat:.3f}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Compare fit to histogram\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,5))\n",
    "axes.hist(filtered, density=True, histtype='stepfilled',\n",
    "         alpha=0.2, label='Samples',bins=bins)\n",
    "axes.plot(bins, stats.skewnorm.pdf(bins, a_hat, loc_hat, scale_hat),\n",
    "         'k-', lw=2, label='Fit')\n",
    "axes.set_xlabel('Temperature (deg C)')\n",
    "axes.set_ylabel('Probability Density')\n",
    "axes.legend(loc='best', frameon=False)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Solving an Initial Value Problem with scipy.integrate"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 600x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from scipy import integrate\n",
    "\n",
    "# Parameters\n",
    "T_air = 15.0      # °C\n",
    "k = 0.1           # hr^-1 cooling rate\n",
    "T0 = 25.0         # initial ocean mixed layer temperature (°C)\n",
    "t_span = (0, 48)  # hours\n",
    "t_eval = np.linspace(*t_span, 200)\n",
    "\n",
    "# ODE system\n",
    "def cooling(t, T):\n",
    "    return -k * (T - T_air)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Solve\n",
    "sol = integrate.solve_ivp(cooling, t_span, [T0], t_eval=t_eval)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 5))\n",
    "axes.plot(sol.t, sol.y[0], label=\"Water temp\")\n",
    "axes.axhline(T_air, color=\"gray\", linestyle=\"--\", label=\"Air temp\")\n",
    "axes.set_xlabel(\"Time (hours)\")\n",
    "axes.set_ylabel(\"Temperature (°C)\")\n",
    "axes.legend()\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()"
   ]
  }
 ],
